						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">To me there seems to be enough range within the game that there should be room for both people who like to play solo and people who like to group.  I am starting to think that what should occur is that when a person is playing on their own they should be tougher and when they group they should have their all around power scaled back  That allows for grouping to occur while not punishing solo players.  This would also mean that it is arbitrary whether one groups or not.  I fail to see why group orientated players should get so many distinct advantageous over solo players, even to the point that a really poor group can out level/out earn and progress through tougher areas then a sound solo player.  
<br />

<br />
Just because the game has many people in it, ie is a mmog, says nothing to me about how those people should relate.  There could be all the people in the world playing, whether they group or not though will be endorsed and allowed or even forced by the consturction of the engine and its compoenents.  This game could easily be turned into a pure solo fest, or a pure group fest, there is nothing inherent in its design that baises it either way.
<br />

<br />
So I think that would be the best solution, scale back the power of groups and mobs in general.  This would allow for soloists to take on challenging level appropriate content without being stuck in a grind and would allow groups to do the same.  I still think there should be slight advantage confered by grouping, but nowehere near the point it is at now where one must group to play the game as it should be played.
<br />

<br />
 Alternatively a few other solutions come to mind.  One would be having certain gear out there that is very powerful but cannot be used in groups, or gets scaled down in group situations.  Another alternative would be having servers completely designated for solo players where again, mobs are made more in line with solo content so that <span style="font-style: italic">it is possible, but very difficult</span> to take on an epic of your own level if you have the best gear, are on top of your game, etc...  I dont like this solution in particular though because it would probably preclude grouping as an option and at times I think most solo players enjoy grouping and I agree with steppy that a good group beats the pants off of solo play much of the time, but when I dont feel partcularly sociable, or when the only other players that are LFG are meat puppets then I really don't think that I should have to resort to errandboy II behavior (ie running here, runnig there, journey is half the fun, whatever) or engaging the same repetative encounters that are "appropriate" or resorting to zones like harcalve where the devs have obviously just generated a higher reward scale as a incentive for people to purchase their product.
<br />

<br />
I honestly see the best solution as allowing soloist greater power, or scaling back the strength of mobs for them.
<br />

<br />
"Well what about people who like to group?" you might say, or "This will make it more difficult for people to find groups."  That is fine, but this is how I see it.  If you like to group, go ahead, go find other people who prefentialy group, but I think it a crime that this should influence the design so as to force those who would naturally prefer to solo into a group.  I don't care if it is tough finding a group, find another person who feels likewise and stick to him like glue, form a guild whatever, just please don't suggest that the inherent design of the game should be such as to influence all players to conform to your preferential play style...
<br />

<br />
It is not unfair because I see no reason why groups should be given innate advantage, the should, IMO, be more social entities then game requirements.  What about the realism factor, some might ask?  It is unrealistic to scale things like that, they might add.  Well with patrons, such scaling ocurs anyway so it is not like it would be a break from stride.
<br />

<br />
The beauty of this solution would be that could allow for ALL classes being viable choices for being soloist.  It would also leave free reign to play group, or solo or any combinatoin thereof. It would not punish groups or soloists, it just would reduce the preferential rewarding of group play over solo play that currently dominates the gamescape.  Thus it would be at once less manipualtive and coercive of play style whilst still totally being open to either.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
